{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"customable-detoxicant-eyra","description":"## Summary\n\nWhile certifying closes during the config-prune/identity epic, ticket READS disagreed with the authoritative on-disk state, causing a long misdiagnosis (I believed closes weren't signing when they were). The user's hunch — and mine — is a CACHING layer serving stale ticket state relative to freshly-written events, likely affecting other ticket operations too. This is a scoped INVESTIGATION for a separate session, not a known-root-cause fix.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n\n1. Close a work ticket so the completion-verifier signs an attestation (in_progress -> closed, gate on).\n2. Immediately read it two ways:\n   - `rebar show <id> --output llm` and inspect the `attestations` map.\n   - `rebar verify-signature <id> --kind completion-verifier`.\n\n## Expected vs Actual\n\n- **Expected:** both agree — if verify-signature certifies, `show`'s attestations map should include the `completion-verifier` entry.\n- **Actual (observed this session):** `show --output llm` reported `attestations: {}` (empty) for the epic 8d27, 297d, 1787, and ad48, while `rebar verify-signature <id> --kind completion-verifier` reported **'certified'** for all four, and SIGNATURE.json events were present on disk in each ticket dir. So the signed attestation existed + certified, but the show read-path did not reflect it. (Note: earlier in the session, `show --output llm` DID surface attestations for another ticket (c366) — so the inconsistency is state/timing-dependent, not a flat format gap.)\n\n## Corroborating second data point (same 'stale cache' family)\n\nThe reconciler inbound-signing test (test_inbound_signing_9e76) had to call `_seam._ATTRIBUTION_CACHE.clear()` before driving `_write_event_file`: an identity created mid-process was NOT resolved because attribution is cached per-repo_root for the process lifetime (a pre-identity miss was cached). A real reconciler process starts with the identity already present so it's fine in prod, but it confirms a per-process cache that can serve stale identity/attribution state.\n\n## Hypotheses to investigate (separate session)\n\n- The `show` / reducer read-path may serve a cached/compacted SNAPSHOT that lags freshly-appended events (SIGNATURE events written at close), so the attestations map renders stale/empty until the cache is invalidated or the snapshot recompacted.\n- Per-process caches (`_ATTRIBUTION_CACHE`, any reducer/state cache) may not invalidate on same-process writes (compaction-on-close, reopen->close cycles, sign_manifest).\n- Interaction with compact-on-close: closing compacts the ticket; the attestation is written around/after compaction — a race or cache-ordering issue could drop it from the read view.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Root cause identified for why `rebar show --output llm` `attestations` disagreed with `verify-signature` / on-disk SIGNATURE events (reproduce deterministically).\n- [ ] Determine the scope: which ticket read operations (show, list, ready, next-batch, deps, --output llm vs default) can serve stale state relative to just-written events, and under what triggers (compact-on-close, reopen->close, in-process writes).\n- [ ] Either fix the read-path to be consistent with the store (invalidate/refresh the cache after writes) or document the invariant + a supported way to force a fresh read.\n- [ ] Regression test that a freshly-signed completion attestation is visible in the same read surfaces that verify-signature certifies.","id":"8d44-d236-0602-4d47","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":["identity","caching","investigate","read-consistency"],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Ticket read-path shows stale state vs on-disk/verify — completion attestations appear ABSENT in `show` though verify-signature certifies (caching?)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784048824962125001,"uuid":"2febea83-2d10-443d-95f3-6748ca1b2fc6"}